Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Halve any large cauliflower florets. Pop the @cauliflower florets{300%g} onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer. When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden brown and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the green beans and chop into thirds.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{0.25%tsp} and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While the rice cooks, heat a #large frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil). Once hot, add the @desiccated coconut{15%g} and cook, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Watch it like a hawk as it can burn easily.

Transfer to a #bowl{} and set aside.

Heat a drizzle of oil in the (now empty) frying pan on medium heat. Once hot, add the garlic, @Sri Lankan style curry powder{1%tbsp} and @tomato puree{30%ml} to the pan. Cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the @coconut milk{200%ml}, green beans, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce. Stir to combine, bring to a boil, then lower the heat and simmer gently until slightly thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> Add a splash of water if it gets too thick.

Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lime{½}. Halve the @red chilli{1} lengthways, deseed, then finely chop. Pop the lime zest and chilli into the bowl with the toasted coconut. Squeeze in a quarter of the lime juice, season with @salt{} and mix well to combine. Set the coconut sambol aside.

Once the curry has thickened, season with salt and pepper. Squeeze in the remaining lime juice, stir well, then taste and add more salt, pepper and lime juice if needed. When cauliflower is roasted, add the @carrot{1}(chopped) and cauliflower to the curry and stir through. Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then divide between your #bowls{}. Spoon the Sri Lankan style curry over the top and sprinkle with the coconut sambol. Enjoy!